title: Prusa I3 MKS2 improved Extruder Cover

description.text:
Using the silicone sock I noticed that the small lip at the cover got in contact
with the hot sock and after some time got weak and distorted and pulled the eye
for the fan duct with it downwards.
Not much but so that my sense for symmetry could not bear it.

I improved the great (they could not know I would use a sock) prusa-cover
making a little space for the heat-block covered in the sock for not to touch the
cover. Adding a small vent-hole to that air-pocket to flush it slightly.
Strengthened the bolt-eye for the duct.
Pictures are of a prototype which I had to rework a bit.
With the .STL you certainly get the final design which fits perfectly with https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2578649
Attention!
The duct-hole cuts with the hole for the lower fan-screw. Use a slightly shorter one.

Made with PETG from these guys https://www.3dpsp.de/ as all my other printer parts.
No drooping or degrading at all....
This stuff turned out to be quite fine to process.
It is quite sturdy, no problems with adhesion at all.
And really nice and brilliant colours for a reasonable price.

description.text:
The adventurers were now exploring the depths of an underground city when they came to some beautiful flooring next to a palace that was slowly falling with age. It appeared to have some arabic type influences.
Mosaic tile 4x4 inch with openlock. Also a design placed on a 3mm base with what I call a top cap that can be attached to your own tile preferences. Increase the top cap size by 25% and you can place it on a true tile. There are very clear lines that differentiate each block in the design. Each miniature color tile is an individually separate 3 dimensional piece. In other words, this isn't just a paint trick to a flat piece of tile.
These tiles are meant to add some flavor to an Arabian Nights type adventure such as Al-Qadim.

description.text:
This is my Hypercube Ramps Case. It is a snap together design so that you can quickly open and close it without any screws.
All the parts are easy to print without support structures. I cut 2 threads in the 2mm holes in the mounting plate to screw the ramps mounting screws directly into the plastic. You can also use longer M3 screws (M3x25) and lock them with two M3 nuts.
I also used 5mm high plastic spacers between the mounting plate and the arduino board.
But you can also print the spacers from the download files ("stand_off_pcb.stl")
On the right side I have a cheap 7mm push button (normally open) which i soldered to the reset button on my ramps board.
If you have difficulties at the beginning with the snap-together parts you can use a little bit of grease on all the plastic noses. This helps quite a lot.

PARTS THAT YOU MIGHT NEED:

Mounting brackets

  • 2x M4x8mm Countersunk Screws (mounting brackets)
  • 2x M4 Nuts
  • 2x T-Slot Nuts
  • 2x M5 Screws for the T Slot Nuts

Ramps mounting

  • 2x M3x22mm Cylindric head screws (ramps mounting)
  • 2x 5mm plastic spacers for M3
  • (1x Fan Guard if you like safety)

Addditional Case Parts

  • Kill Switch | https://de.aliexpress.com/item/5Pcs-Red-Cap-PB05A-7mm-2Pin-1NO-Latching-ON-OFF-Mini-Push-Button-Switch/32755775404.html
  • 4x(8x) PC Case fan screws
  • 1x 80mm PC fan ( I am using an old artic cooling pc fan with a neat 3 Speed Slide Switch)

Feel free to remix my design for your needs. You can find the STEP Assembly also in the DOWNLOADS!

title: Tevo Tarantula MKS Board Cable Strain Relief

description.text:
After seeing the strain relief model made by Charles_Snyder (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2451150) I printed one, but It was quite big, needed supports and I couldnt fit the top plate with the fan back on, so I made my own version.

Advantages for this model:

  • minimalistic design
  • no support needed
  • less plastic needed for the print
  • good clearance from the solder on the back of the mks board
  • allows the top plate with the fan to be mounted

The arm and bracket are recreations of the PSU Open-X Re-design in openscad. The original re-design changed the angle from the horizontal that the arm holds the bearings from 30 to 45. I've made that a parameter that defaults to 45. If you change it, you'll want to change the height and shoulder parameters to adjust the position at which the bearing is held also. With non-default parameters, you can generate the bracket as it was in the re-design, but it defaults to produce my changes:
  • radius of the bracket at the top is reduced so that it won't protrude above the top of the carriage.
  • the slot was replaced by a simple screw hole
  • the cylindrical extension stem beside the bearing was reduced by 1 mm.
  • the extension was also tapered so that it is not flush with the bearing.
    • The carriage is an edit of the Open-X Carriage mk2. With non-default parameters you can generate the mk2 or the original open-x carriage, but with defaults, you get my changes to the mk2:
  • one of the recesses for a screw head is removed because I attach an opto-endstop flag there.
  • The interior ribs and the holes for mounting a wade extruder oriented along the x axis are removed. I prefer to have the open space rather than the mounting option. I've added a thick curved inner wall to make up for the loss of the ribs. Printed at 100% infill, it is very sturdy.
    • An additional module is provided that renders the assembled parts along with x bars and bearings. This can be useful for visualizing the effects of your edits.

Instructions for changing parameters are included in comments at the top of the openx.scad file. RP Parts 1 x Carriage 1 x Arm 2 x Bracket Nuts and Bolts, Standard Parts 14 x M4-16 screws 14 x M4 nuts ~30 x M4 washers 10 x 624 Ball Bearings 1 x X-Axis opto flag A package of zip ties Assembly is similar to the original Open-X except that there are two brackets instead of one. title: Y-axis motor cooling fan bracket for Anet A6
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
The first thing we at VintageElectronics.ca noticed when we started using our new Anet A6 (a Prussa i3 clone) was that during prolonged printing at high speeds (400-500%) the Y-axis stepper motor overheated, stretched the nylon belt and at some point the layers shifted by as much as 4-6mm (1/4").

We designed and installed the bracket for a regular 12V 40mm fan on the back wall near the motor, and powered the fan from the main PS.

That completely solved the motor overheating issue. While the Y-axis motor was hot to touch previously, it is now barely warm to touch. The nylon belt no longer stretches and our prints come out perfect.

title: Spool Holder for Kodama Trinus
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a spool holder for the Kodama Trinus, that prints on the Trinus itself and does not require any extra hardware than the one coming with the printer itself (i.e.: it uses the two screws provided).

Any feedback (negative or positive) is welcome! :)

Printer:

Kodama Trinus

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1

Infill:

60%

Notes:

Both pieces are meant to be printed flat (as in: the only orientation that you can print them without support). This is important in order to maximise the strength of each piece, relative to the direction it will be stressed the most.

You will need to print 1 main body and 2 arms. I don't think it's possible to fit the three of them in the same print though (I printed the main body alone, and the 2 arms together).

Unless you have heated and levelled printing bed, you ought to print this with a raft. This is because the parts are rather long (for the Trinus size, that's it) and they will:

A) tend to warp and detach from the plate
B) be affected a lot by any defect in the standard build plate levelling

For the body, you should have the raft only 1mm larger than the body, as otherwise you may not be able to fit the piece on the building plate in the slicer (it only fits diagonally, and it almost reaches the very edge of the plate).

While you are free to print the main body at any resolution you may like (I printed mine at 0.1), you should print the arms at 0.1 resolution (or less) otherwise you may end up with arms that are too lose in their sockets or fit too tightly in them.

The filament holder works "as is", but should you want to reduce the filament friction across the eyelets, you can thermoform the arms by pouring some boiling water on their tip, inserting a pen in the eyelet and twisting it ~45° (see picture).

I suspect this is highly unnecessary, but the idea is that this way the contact surface between filament and eyelet will be reduced to a minimum.

Twist & Shout!

This is my very first project, so I had to learn everything from scratch: from how to use a CAD sofware, to how to design objects meant to be mechanically stressed, to operating the printer... so feedback on what I did wrong is very welcome.

That said: this thing has already being used and abused for a couple of hundreds hours and its holding up well and working great.

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tRQ6UkV8KyY
Firstly, this isn't really a theremin, it only changes pitch, instead of pitch and volume. Also it changes pitch using a reading from a distance sensor instead of using radio waves, but I thought that autonomous theremin was the best description of what this thing is. It was made using mostly spare 3D printer parts, as well as some other bits and pieces I had lying around the house. It is controlled using an arduino. I've uploaded a rough circuit diagram as well as the code. If you've watched the video I've attached of this thing trying to play the Rick and Morty theme, you'll have realised how out of tune it is. It is limited by the accuracy and speed of the distance sensor. so if anyone else tries this, in order to play a recognisable song, you'll need a really accurate distance sensor.

Materials
3D Printed Parts

  • Base + Stand (these two parts form a casing for the electronics)
  • Plate (this is the part that moves up and down that the distance sensor detects)
  • Upper Bracket (Holds together the rods at the top and the bearing that the timing belt moves around)
  • Bearing guide for 608zz bearing (I used the one designed by brnrd https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:20032)

Other Parts

  • 2x linear rods
  • 2x linear bearings

  • 4x brackets for linear rods (these could easily be printed) https://www.ebay.com/itm/4pc-8mm-500mm-Linear-Rod-Rail-Shafts-Optical-Axis-4-SCS8UU-Bearing-Blocks-Kit/311802254782?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649

  • GT2 Timing Belt https://www.ebay.com/itm/LearCNC-GT2-Timing-Belt-2mm-Pitch-6mm-width-Reprap-CNC-RAMPS-Prusa-3D-Printer/201147542781?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649

  • 20 tooth GT2 pulley https://www.banggood.com/162030T-GT2-Aluminum-Timing-Drive-Pulley-For-DIY-3D-Printer-p-1001266.html?rmmds=myorder&cur_warehouse=CN

  • 608zz bearing https://www.banggood.com/Wholesale-10Pcs-8-x-22-x-7mm-Metal-Sealed-Shielded-Deep-Groove-Ball-Bearing-608zz-p-62636.html?rmmds=myorder&cur_warehouse=CN

  • Arduino Uno

  • Wire

  • A4988 Stepper Driver https://www.banggood.com/3D-Printer-A4988-Reprap-Stepping-Stepper-Step-Motor-Driver-Module-p-88765.html?rmmds=myorder&cur_warehouse=CN

  • 47 microFarad Capacitor (put in parallel with the power input for the stepper driver)

  • Potentiometer for controlling volume https://www.ebay.com/itm/10pcs-50K-ohm-3362P-Trim-Pot-Trimmer-Potentiometer-3362P-503/201415102052?epid=1331627127&hash=item2ee5468e64:g:5XEAAOSwajVUTaeN

  • Nema 17 Stepper motor https://www.banggood.com/NEMA-17-42-Hybrid-Stepper-Motor-5mm-Round-Shaft-Two-Phase-Four-Line-Stepper-Motor-p-1148356.html?rmmds=search&cur_warehouse=CN

  • IR Sensor (I wanted to use a remote to control this robot, but if you wanted it would be easy to replace this with a button) https://www.banggood.com/Universal-IR-Infrared-Receiver-Head-With-Iron-Shell-TL1838-VS1838B-1838-38Khz-p-1204379.html?rmmds=search&cur_warehouse=CN

  • Distance Sensor (I used an HCSR04 ultrasonic distance sensor, but if this thing is going to work, you'd need something more accurate) https://www.ebay.com/itm/1pcs-Ultrasonic-Module-HC-SR04-Distance-Measuring-Transducer-Sensor-for-Arduino/400985326881?epid=1638465117&hash=item5d5c968521:g:kLQAAOxyNyFS-xFw

This is a stereo microphone bar designed to take clip-on lavalier micrphones and position them either in the ORTF configuration or in X-Y.

It was specifically designed to take cardioid Clippy microphones from FEL Communications using Primo EM-184 capsules, but other cardioid clip-on lavalier microphones should work as well.

If you are using Clippy microphones the ORTF spacing and angles will be correct, but the X-Y position doesn't result in a completely coincident pair. The capsules will be separated by about 30mm. Other microphones will have slightly different geometries that will change the positioning of the diaphragms.

Please be aware this will only create an accurate stereo image if the microphones being used have a cardioid pickup pattern. Omni microphones will result in a slightly spaced image when used in ORTF, but it won't be ideal. Omni microphones really need a wider spacing or a baffle to create a strong stereo image.

Supplies for building a pair of cardioid EM-184 Clippy microphones can be had from FEL Communications (Micbooster.com):

http://micbooster.com/

The three holes in the bar are sized for 1/4"-20 screws. The two outer holes are through-holes for mounting other gear on the bar. The center hole is threaded to mount onto a standard photographic tripod or light stand. If you want to use this on a microphone stand you will need an adapter (or just modify the thread to suit).

2 Ikea LACK tables, few screws, couple of hours, and let's built your 3D printer enclosure.

This one is designed to be really simple to open - the full top is removable for full access - and every fixation part is design to be as much as possible clean or invisible.

What you need :

Obviously, at least 2 Ikea Lack tables :)
4x Base Rehausseur
1x each Rehausseur PIED (1, 2, 3 & 4)
3x Fixation Haute
1x Charniere Haute
2x Charniere Porte

3mm plexiglass

How to build it :

Preparation :

Redrill to 6mm the transversal hole in each "Base Rehausseur" and in each "Rehausseur"
(will soon update and add a 6mm PLA rod to secure and lock the top enclosure)

Drill a big hole, or a lot of small ones, in the base of each leg from the upper table.
With a wood chisel and a hammer, gently remove the piece of wood inserted into each leg and its glue.
.
Base table :

Screw down on each corner the 4x "Base Rehausseur" (I used 3.5x35mm wood screws)

Top table :

Insert "Fixation Haute" on the leg screw (the big one) and, and this is actually the hardest part, screw the leg into the top table...

title: Prusa i3 MK2 LED Lighting Mount (Improved)

description.text:
So I originally designed the Prusa i3 MK2 LED Lighting mount a while back and have used it since to success. But there were some flaws.

1) The z axis couldn't home without hitting the right mount.
2) The mounts were flimsy and fragile
3) the amount of soldering required to do this was insane (using LED strips)
4) This wire mounting clips at were kind of useless. I replaced them with holes for zip ties.

I fixed the z axis homing issue by making the front part of the attachment point, to the frame, thinner.

I fixed the fragility of the mounts by adding more material between the arm and the light mount part.

I used an LED light panel (though you could use light strips like in the first one) instead of the led strips. The panels I used were actually dome light replacements for a car but they worked ok. I could fit two of the panels per arm. Here is the part I used: https://www.ebay.com/itm/10X-Festoon-T10-BA9S-White-LED-48SMD-Panel-Interior-Dome-Map-Light-Bulb-Lamp-12V/251424860511?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2060353.m2749.l2649

Update

After a day the light panels were falling off with the provided adhesive. I am still using them but ended up using hot glue to adhere them to the plastic.

These consume a lot more power than the strips did -- so we will see how it works out.

Either way -- even if I end up going back to the strip lights this mount is going to be a lot better than the first!

I uploaded the Fusion 360 and the STEP file for anyone who needs. To get the other one just flip it.

EDIT

Yes I know I have build tak on the bed -- I couldn't find any decent PEI sheets so I threw what I had on it. :)

description.text: Here's one of the 2" prop frames I've made, designed for 20mm stacks and 9mm M2 bolt pattern motors, with 50mm props. The stack is run diagonally for the smallest footprint possible, and clearance to the stack is pretty tight (but could be tighter, but would just mean for more negated thrust over the FC). I've included my minimalistic 25 degree camera mount but of course you can use any 20mm footprint mount you like. Pictured is my build running Lizard 95 prop guards with pushrod tubing for reinforcement. I found that without the tubing to connect the guards, I had fairly noticeable vibrations, but after adding the tubing it flies awesome with no resonance whatsoever. My implementation involves having M2 standoffs that thread into the four FC bolts, and if you do the same (I did it so my battery mounts flush) you'll want to tap the holes with a metal M2 screw before trying to screw the nylon standoffs in. For motor screws you'll want M2x7 if running Lizard prop guards (3mm thick) and M2x4 if running commando. Enjoy!

Here are two roughly spherical ornaments with windows so that the interior is visible. Both interiors show outlines of a cat; one a single image, the second three small cat images at the corners of an equilateral triangle.

The ornaments are related in that both are derived from the same polylhedron - a Truncated Rhombicosidodecahedron - http://dmccooey.com/polyhedra/CanonicalTruncatedRhombicosidodecahedron.html - from the visual polyhedra web site - http://dmccooey.com/polyhedra/ . Faces that occur in one ornament are missing from the second and vice versa.

The polyhedron has, as faces, 12 regular decagons, 30 octagons, 20 regular hexagons, and 60 isosceles trapezoids. In the first ornament the decagonal and hexagonal faces were left blank; in the second the octagonal faces were omitted. Windows were created by the omission of additional faces. The remaining faces were decorated with stars, snowflakes, and a cat image.

This forms part of a now abandoned project of mine.
I had planned to use this as part of a laser fence system, complete with adjustable mounting etc.

I had intended to run this from a variety of power sources, most notably a 12v battery.

I have since discovered cheaper and more effective options.
To make this component of the system you will need:

1 X Laser module from Jaycar Cat No: XC4490 AUD $5
1 X 5V regulator board AMS1117 5V (Aliexpress) AUD $0.25
4 X 1N4004 Diodes (Jaycar)

Assemble the diodes (optional) into a bridge rectifier arrangement for polarity protection.
Connect these between the input wires and the 5V regulator.

Connect the output of the 5V regulator to the GND and S pins of the laser
GND to Negative, S to positive.

Insert into case, and glue in.

WARNING: if like me, you plan to pot the laser for waterproofing, be careful, as you may screw up the collimator.

Hot glue is a bad idea, Two part epoxy is much better, but keep it clear of the rear of the laser aperture and collimator.

This project assumes you know not to look directly into a laser or do idiotic things like point them at aircraft - I'm not responsible.

These are the walls and handles for my SelfieBot project guide on the Adafruit Learning System. These parts are combined with three laser cut acrylic panels to make a case for a Raspberry Pi-powered selfie camera. The walls are too big to fit on the bed of most printers. Split into halves (or smaller) to fit on your printer. To attach the pieces after printing, I used epoxy glue.

Because these parts will be combined with laser cut parts, it is very important to calculate the shrinkage factor of your print material and scale the models up accordingly so that the parts will fit together. This can be done by creating a 2" cube in your CAD program, printing it, and then measuring your print.

I recommend scaling the walls up based on this shrinkage calculation before cutting the models into printable pieces.

description.text:
Bugsy Jr. was made with one real purpose in mind, to look adorable next to a typical 250 quad. However, it turns out he is a proper quad in his own right!

Keep in mind, this is a fragile little guy. The main plates are only 1mm thick, and depending on the material used can crack easy. On the upside, it is quite fast to print more.

Currently I get ~5 min of flight time going easy on it.

Print using a rigid filament, particularly for the arms, to reduce vibration/noise issues

Print List:

  • Main Plate (2)
  • Arm (4)
  • Top Plate (1)
  • MotorSpacer(4) (TPU)
  • BatteryStrap(2) (TPU) - Narrow straps fit bottom battery mount slots as well as top
  • Camera Mount(2) (TPU) Print the mount twice, one time Mirrored

Parts List(as Pictured):

  • 0703 10000kv Motors (4)
  • Betaflight F3 Micro 6A 2S 4-In-1 Brushless ESC OSD Flight Controller Micro Cube
  • XT30 Battery cable
  • Makerfire 350mAh 60C 2S 7.4V Lipo
  • Props: 55mm, 60mm should fit, haven't tried yet

Hardware:

  • M2 Nylon assortment, designed for 15mm standoffs between top and main plate

History:

  • 12/06/17 - Fixed a misplaced mounting hole in top plate
  • 12/02/17 - Further updated arms, nubs on end to protect motors. Re-oriented arm screw holes to help prevent them getting ripped out in a forward collision.
  • 11/30/17 - Stronger arms, much less vibration. Modified main plate for passing wiring between plates. Replaced original top plate with notched plate, modified holes for AIO camera.
  • 11/26/17 - Updated screw hole sizes on everything to reduce slop in arms and body. Use a 2mm or 5/64 bit to clean up holes as necessary. Added Narrow Battery straps and strap holes to main frame for bottom mounted battery.
  • 11/25/17 - Added the camera mount
  • 11/25/17 - Added a top plate with a slight front notch for FPV view
